Results

Results

Mean difference explanation

A key statistic I used to compare playoff and non-playoff teams is the mean of their differences of each year for a given variable.

Results

Mean difference explanation

The differences of means (playoff minus non-playoff) from the previous table

Results

Mean difference explanation

The mean of the differences of Runs Scored from 2005-2015

## [1] 69.33802

What this tells us is that, on average from 2005-2015, playoff teams are scoring 69.33 more runs per year than non-playoff teams. Not only are they scoring more runs, they are scoring more runs every year even when only comparing to the top non-playoff teams. (plot on next slide)

Results

Playoff vs. non-playoff

Similarly to Runs Scored, Hits and Walks topped the batting statistics, while Hits Allowed and Walks Allowed topped the pitching statistics favoring playoff teams.

Okay, but this is expected, right? Shouldn't the teams that can score more runs and get more hits win? Not so fast!

Results

Correlation of playoff team batting variables

Results

Correlation of non-playoff team batting variables

Results

Correlation

  • Runs (R) to Win Percent: Playoff teams have a weak positive correlation of Runs to Win Percent (0.25), while non-playoff teams have a moderate positive correlation (.40). We have seen previously that Playoff teams are scoring more runs overall. The low correlation of Runs to Win Percent could potentially be a sign that it's not the number of runs but the efficiency of Runs that sets playoff teams apart.

  • Home runs (HR) to Runs and Walks (BB) to Runs: Playoff teams have a moderate positive correlation of HR to Runs (0.55), while non-playoff teams of a strong positive correlation (0.67). The reverse is true of Walks to Runs. Playoff teams are Walking more and hitting more Home Runs as seen previously but potentially are spreading out their sources of runs more effectively. This is relevant so that if a few of their players go cold, others can pick them up.

Results

League-wide trends

The league-wide trends in the MLB caught my eye more than the differences between teams of varying playoff status.

I saw that runs and hits were down, so I thought "Okay, it probably has a lot to do with the performance enhancing drug crackdown":

Then, I saw the strikeouts and walks numbers…

Results

League-wide trends: Strikeouts

Results

League-wide trends: Walks

Results

League-wide trends

When hits, runs, and walks are down, and strikeouts are up, you cannot blame drug-testing, large, pitcher-friendly stadiums, or other external factors. Either the hitters are getting worse, or the pitchers are getting better. I must explore further, but it seems logical to say that if hitters' numbers are low league-wide for numbers that aren't improved by external factors but rather by natural ability, then it's plausible that pitchers are just doing a better job at adjusting to hitters than the reverse.

  • The shift
  • Hitter weak zones

Conclusion

Conclusion

Closing remarks

Especially at a time in baseball when the offensive numbers are down and the defensive side has the upper hand, every scoring opportunity must be taken and sources of runs must be varied. Every opportunity missed is another potential loss, and the opportunities are only getting fewer. The teams who make the playoffs are best at this. However, efficiency and varied source of runs might not be the only solution. The defense has adjusted; can the offense adjust back?

Conclusion

Next steps

While I could make some remarks by eyeballing plots, data science is more than that. Upon further reading and given more time, I would

  • run significance tests to compare the difference in mean differences and variable correlations
  • further divide the playoff and non-playoff teams. I would check the bottom 3-5 playoffs teams against the top 3-5 non-playoff teams
  • do a deeper player-level analysis to see what I can uncover
